If a civilian is assaulted by a soldier, he dare not prosecute before the centuri0n3 for all the soldiers are hostile and civilian witnesses are afraid to appear (ll. 7—34). The genuineness of this fragment has often been denied from the times of the scholiast to our own. But it is quoted as genuine by Servius and Priscian, and in both style and content is not unworthy of Juvenal.
